Effectiveness enters the picture because parameters chosen for fuzz-testing may require tuning.
For example, the use of a certain set of seeds (input files) may make a fuzzing session X better than another session Y in which a different seed set was chosen.
Better in what way, you ask?
Sadly, there is no universal metric to gauge "betterness": Some meaningful metrics that are broadly considered good are program coverage (e.g., lines of code tested by fuzz testing), bugs uncovered, time to expose bugs etc.
The basic idea is that, should fuzzer configuration A perform better on one or more of these metrics than another configuration B, then we can make fuzz testing more efficient i.e., save energy, dedicate resources elsewhere etc.

